chronous": false, "params": [{"name": "value", "type": {"name": "Any", "xref": {"fqname": "typing.Any", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}, "default": null}, {"name": "spec", "type": {"name": "Type", "xref": {"fqname": "typing.Type", "project": "--std--"}, "params": [{"name": "T", "xref": {"fqname": "T", "project": null}, "params": null}]}, "default": null}], "returns": {"name": "T", "xref": {"fqname": "T", "project": null}, "params": null}, "documentation": ["This is the main entry point of the validobj module.\nValidates and processes the input value based on the provided\nspecification.\n\n# Parameters\n\nvalue\n\n: The value to be processed.\n\nspec\n\n: The target specification.\n\n# Returns\n\nvalue\n\n: The processed form of value. This can be the input value\n  itself if only a (recursive) type check was performed\n  or a more structured output, based on the type of the\n  specification.\n\n# Raises\n\nValidationError\n\n: Raised if the input cannot be coerced to the spec. An\n  appropriate subclass defined in {py:mod}`validobj.errors`\n  will contain more specific information as well `__cause__`\n  fields chained as neccessary.\n\n# Notes\n\nThe parameters are described in detail in {ref}`Input and output <inout>`.\n\nThe error handling is described in {ref}`Errors <errors>`.\n\n# Examples\n\nCheck that a given input is a mapping of string to integer:\n\n```\n.. doctest::\n\n    >>> validobj.parse_input({'key1': 1, 'key2': 2}, typing.Mapping[str, int])\n    {'key1': 1, 'key2': 2}\n```\n\nCoerce the input to a dataclass of a valid shape:\n\n```\n.. doctest::\n\n    >>> import dataclasses\n    >>> @dataclasses.dataclass\n    ... class Data:\n    ...     key: str\n    ...     key2: int = 4\n    ...\n    >>> validobj.parse_input({'key': 'Hello'}, Data)\n    Data(key='Hello', key2=4)\n```\n\nFind a list item that does not conform to the specification:\n\n```\n.. doctest::\n\n    >>> import typing\n    >>> try:\n    ...    validobj.parse_input([1,2,'tres'], typing.List[int])\n    ... except validobj.ValidationError as e:\n    ...    e.wrong_index\n    ...\n    2\n```\n"]}], "variables": [{"name": "validobj.validation.HAVE_TYPED_DICT", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.validation.HAVE_TYPED_DICT", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.validation.HAVE_ANNOTATED", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.validation.HAVE_ANNOTATED", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.validation.HAVE_TYPE_ALIAS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.validation.HAVE_TYPE_ALIAS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.validation.HAVE_UNION_TYPE", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.validation.HAVE_UNION_TYPE", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.validation.T", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "validobj.validation.parse_input", "xref": {"fqname": "validobj.validation.parse_input", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "validobj.custom", "documentation": ["Tools for {ref}`custom validation <custom>` of types.\nWorks with Python 3.9 only.\n\n```\n.. testsetup::\n\n    import typing\n\n    from validobj.custom import Parser\n```\n"], "functions": [{"name": "validobj.custom.Parser", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "func", "type": {"name": "Callable", "xref": {"fqname": "typing.Callable", "project": "--std--"}, "params": [{"name": "", "xref": null, "params": [{"name": "Any", "xref": {"fqname": "typing.Any", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}]}, {"name": "T", "xref": {"fqname": "T", "project": null}, "params": null}]}, "default": null}], "returns": {"name": "Type", "xref": {"fqname": "typing.Type", "project": "--std--"}, "params": [{"name": "T", "xref": {"fqname": "T", "project": null}, "params": null}]}, "documentation": ["Read the type annotations of `func` and return a\n{py:class}`typing.Annotated` with the function's return type as the set\ntype and the requisite metadata so that `func` is used by\n{py:func}`validobj.parse_input`.\n\n# Parameters\n\nfunc\n\n: The wrapped function. It should have one positional parameter. If the\n  parameter is annotated, Validobj will cast the input consitently with\n  the annotation before presenting it to the function.\n\n# Returns\n\nannotated\n\n: Annotation of the return type of the function with two metadata parameters:\n  {py:class}`InputType` with the type annotation of the first parameter and\n  {py:class}`Validator` with the function itself.\n\n# Examples\n\nAdd support for {py:class}`decimal.Decimal`.\n\n```\n.. doctest::\n    :pyversion: >= 3.9\n\n    >>> import typing\n    >>> import decimal\n    >>> from validobj import parse_input, ValidationError\n    >>> from validobj.custom import Parser\n    >>> def to_decimal(inp: typing.Union[str, int, float]) -> decimal.Decimal:\n    ...     try:\n    ...         return decimal.Decimal(inp)\n    ...     except decimal.InvalidOperation as e:\n    ...         raise ValidationError(\"Invalid decimal\") from e\n    ...\n    >>> Decimal = Parser(to_decimal)\n    >>> print(Decimal)\n    typing.Annotated[decimal.Decimal, InputType(typing.Union[str, int, float]), Validator(<function to_decimal at ...>)]\n    >>> parse_input(0.5, Decimal)\n    Decimal('0.5')\n```\n"]}], "variables": [{"name": "validobj.custom.T", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [{"name": "validobj.custom.InputType", "bases": [], "methods": [{"name": "validobj.custom.InputType.__init__", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "type", "type": {"name": "Type", "xref": {"fqname": "typing.Type", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "validobj.custom.InputType.__repr__", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "class_variables": [], "instance_variables": [], "in